{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17497086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17497086"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:03:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:03:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1470"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1470"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.54,0.24,0.15,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1470"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43981"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1470"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1470"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28969"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"768"},{"type":"tags","id":"1309"},{"type":"tags","id":"2189"},{"type":"tags","id":"6053"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6083"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6741"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15650"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45226"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43981"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn eight-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department (ED) carried in by her father in obvious distress. The father states that she was wrestling with her brother when a particularly vicious body slam left her in extreme pain and inability to weight bear on the right leg. On examination, there is obvious swelling of the right ankle which is exquisitely tender on palpation. There is a palpable dorsalis pedis and posterior tibial pulse with brisk capillary refill. This is no sensory loss over the dorsal and plantar surface of the foot and she is able to wiggle her big toe. Subsequent imaging is ordered and shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the radiological findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Salter Harris type 1","Salter Harris type 2","Salter Harris type 3","Salter Harris type 4","Salter Harris type 5"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Salter-Harris classification system is frequently used to describe paediatric fractures involving the physial (growth) plate. There are five types and include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EType 1 is a simple epiphysis shift resulting in physial separation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EType 2, where the epiphysis takes with it a fragment of adjacent metaphyseal bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EType 3 is a fracture through the epiphysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EType 4 is partial epiphysis with distal shaft fragment shift.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EType 5 is epiphyseal compression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment of these paediatric injuries depend on the age of the patient, bone remodelling potential, and degree of displacement of the fracture fragment/s.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA helpful mnemonic for recalling the types of fractures is \u003Cstrong\u003ESALTR\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ES\u003C/strong\u003Elipped (Type 1)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA\u003C/strong\u003Ebove or away from physial plate (Type 2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EL\u003C/strong\u003Eower than plate (Type 3)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET\u003C/strong\u003Ehrough both sides of plate (Type 4)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ER\u003C/strong\u003Euined or rammed plate (Type 5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The Salter-Harris classification system is used to grade paediatric fractures that involve the growth plate (also known as physis or physial plate)."],"references":["Marson BA, Ng J, Myint Y, et al. Management of \u2018low-risk\u2019 ankle fractures in children: a systematic review.A nn R Coll Surg Engl 2019; 101: 539\u201345"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28969"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1470"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16361"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16361"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/23719224-bc77-4f5e-b7d8-2f7b493b5670.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/23719224-bc77-4f5e-b7d8-2f7b493b5670.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":609,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28969"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-03T16:37:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-27T10:03:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1470"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43981"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"